text: Cite this: RSC Adv., 2016, 6, 18946 Received 25th November 2015 Accepted 18th January 2016 Chlamydia is a Gram-negative pathogen which causes several diseases to mankind.1,2 Chlamydia trachomatis is the most common sexually transmitted bacterial pathogen, with 100 million cases per year world wide.3 It also aﬀects 400 million people as the major cause of preventable blindness.4 In addition, genital C. trachomatis infection has been identied as a cofactor that is necessary for the transmission of human immunode- ciency virus (HIV).5 Chlamydia pneumoniae infection is respon- sible for pneumonia fever and respiratory infections in humans.6 These human pathogens are able to evade the host immune system. Homologous proteins are also found in other intracel- lular pathogens such as Legionella pneumophila MIP,7 Chlamydia pneumonia8 and Trypanasoma cruzi.9 Macrophage infectivity cis/trans potentiator isomerase (PPIase) activity7 that can be inhibited by rapamycin and FK506.10 Recently, the 3D structures of Mip proteins from L. aDepartment of Marine Science, School of Marine Sciences, Bharathidasan University, Trichy-620024, India. Vijayan Ramachandran,ab Elavarasi Padmanaban,a Kalaiarasan Ponnusamy,c Subbarao Naidub and Manoharan Natesan*a Macrophage infectivity potentiator (Mip) is the virulence factor from Chlamydia trachomatis that is primarily responsible for causing sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) and blindness. Mip possesses peptidyl-prolyl- cis/trans-isomerase (PPIase) activity that can be inhibited by FK506 or rapamycin. Substitution at the aspartate-142 position by leucine-142 and replacement at the tyrosine-185 position by alanine-185 in the catalytic site strongly reduces the PPIase activity of Mip proteins as reported earlier. There are no experimentally determined structures available for Chlamydia trachomatis Mip and the number of reported cases of blindness and STDs are increasing. Due to these facts, it is very important to design new inhibitors against Mip. So, we have modeled the protein structure by homology modeling. Further, a pharmacophore model and molecular docking simulations were employed to discover Mip inhibitors from a Universal Natural Product Database (UNPD) of 229 358 natural compounds. The docking violaceoruber and Plumarella from Marine coral species emerged as the top candidates. In addition, molecular dynamics (MD) simulations were carried out to analyze the conformational changes behind the molecular mechanism of Mip (native and mutants) for the screened novel lead compounds.

pneumophila and E. coli in complex with the PPIase inhibitors rapamycin11 and FK506,12 respectively have been reported. Also mutation of the Legionella pneumophila Mip protein on catalytic residues at the aspartate-142 position replaced by leucine-142 and the tyrosine-185 position replaced by alanine-185 strongly reduces PPIase activity.13 In order to design a drug for treating chlamydial infections, we constructed an in silico mutagen- esis14,15 model for both important catalytic residues (aspartate- 170 to leucine-170 and tyrosine-213 to alanine-213) of C. tra- chomatis Mip,16 validated the stability of the mutated model. The Universal Natural Products Database (UNPD)17 was created to be a comprehensive resource of natural products for virtual screening. The UNPD consists of 229 358 molecules ltered based on Lipinski and ADME properties. Further, we have built a pharmacophore model based on the available structural data in the protein data bank comprised of major interactions between native inhibitors and Mip active-site residues. Using our pharmacophore model, we were able to rank the active mole- cules and the unt compounds were discarded. Further we have docked the hit compounds of the native and mutant C. tracho- matis Mip to the known inhibitor rapamycin to determine the binding aﬃnity. Interestingly, 2 compounds were selected for molecular dynamics studies to analyze the stability of the native and mutant model in complex with hit compounds. The primary sequence of the Chlamydia trachomatis Mip protein was retrieved from the UniProt database (accession number: P26623) (http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot). A sequence similarity search for the protein against other sequences with existing structural information in the Protein Data Bank (http:// www.rcsb.org/pdb) was performed using PSI-BLAST [http:// ww.ncbi.nlm.hih.gov/blast]. The crystal structure of Legionella pneumophila Mip (PDB ID: 1FD9 with 2.4 A resolution) was selected as a template, having 35% sequence identity with the target. To analyze conservation of the protein sequence, Chla- mydia trachomatis Mip and Legionella pneumophila Mip were aligned by Clustal W.18 Gaps were inserted into the sequences to obtain an optimal alignment, as represented in Fig. 1. The 3D structure of Chlamydia trachomatis Mip was modeled using the Modeller,19 and visualized using Discovery Studio20 and PyMOL soware.21 The three-dimensional homology model of the protein was obtained by probability density function with the variable target function procedure in the Cartesian space using the methods of conjugate gradients and molecular dynamics with simulated annealing.19 Twenty homology models were built and energy minimized with the CHARMM force eld,22 with 500 steps of the steepest descent and 1000 steps of the conjugate gradient with a root mean square (rms) gradient of the potential (cid:1)1 at each step. The stereo-chemical energy of 0.001 kcal mol quality of the nal rened model was evaluated using PRO- CHECK.23 The mutant (D170L and Y213A) structure of Cht Mip was built by induced point mutation at positions 170 and 213 of C. trachomatis Mip protein using the SPDB viewer package.13 This structure was energetically optimized by applying the all atom OPLS force eld available in the SPDB viewer package.24

This soware has advanced alignment algorithms to discover various pharmaco- phoric points/features such as hydrogen bond acceptors (HBAs), hydrogen bond donors (HBDs), ring aromatics (RAs), hydrophobic groups (HYPs) and hydrogen bonding vectors on ligands to generate the pharmacophore model of potential inhibitors against Chlamydia trachomatis Mip. We have devel- oped a pharmacophore model based on the crucial interactions between the native inhibitors (FK506 and rapamycin) and active site residues of Mip as a control. The compounds were further energy minimized for 100 steps with the Swiss-PDB viewer with the steepest descent and conjugated gradient algorithms.24

2.5 Virtual screening The hit compounds having specic pharmacophoric features were subjected to molecular docking studies using GOLD (Genetic Optimization for Ligand Docking).28 Hit compounds were docked into the active site to conrm the correct binding mode and to determine the binding aﬃnity. Cambridge Crystallographic Data Center (United Kingdom), GOLD 5.1 program28 uses a genetic algorithm for docking ligands into protein binding sites to explore the full range of ligand conformational exibility with partial exibility of protein. The docking procedure consists of three interrelated components: (a) identication of the binding site (b) a search algorithm to eﬀectively sample the search space (the set of possible ligand positions and conformations on the protein surface) and (c) a scoring function. The GOLD tness score28 is measured based on the formation of protein–ligand hydrogen bond energy (external H-bond), protein–ligand van der Waals (vdW) energy (external vdw), ligand internal vdW energy (internal vdW) and ligand torsional strain energy (internal torsion). Protein coordinates from the representative structure of Chlamydia tra- chomatis Mip and mutant structures obtained from homology modeling were used to dene the active site. The active site was dened with a 10 ˚A radius around rapamycin. NaCl counter ions were included for the requirement of the electro-neutrality condition. Energy was minimized using the steepest descent method. In order to maintain the system in a stable environment (300 k, 1 bar), Berendsen temperature coupling36 and Parrinello–Rah- man pressure coupling37 were employed and the coupling constants were set to 0.1 and 2.0 ps for temperature and pres- sure. LINCS algorithm39 was employed to measure all the constrained bond lengths and the time step was set to 0.002 ps. The complexes in a medium were equilibrated to 100 ps in NPT and NVT ensembles, respectively. Finally, a 20 ns molecular dynamics simulation was carried out for both native and mutant complexes of Chlamydia trachomatis Mip. Results and discussion 3.1 Homology modeling The experimentally determined structure for Chlamydia tra- chomatis Mip was not available in the Protein Data Bank (PDB). Therefore, we have predicted the protein structure of Chlamydia trachomatis Mip by homology modeling, a promising tool for providing insights into the interaction between a drug and receptor. The amino acid sequence of Cht Mip consisting of 243 from UniProt amino Per residue (SAS) ˚A (mutation) RSC Adv., 2016, 6, 18946–18957 | 18951 Fig. 8 (A) Docked conformation of Cht Mi (native) with compound-1 (UNPD175753), (B) docked conformation of D170L Cht Mip (mutant) with compound-1 (UNPD175753), and (C) docked conformation of Y213A Cht Mip (mutant) with compound-1 (UNPD175753).

(http://www.uniprot.org). Sequence alignment of Chlamydia trachomatis (Cht) Mip with Legionella pneumophila Mip was performed using Clustal W to align conserved key residues as shown in Fig. 1. The X-ray structure of Legionella pneumophila Mip at 2.4 ˚A resolution (PDB ID: 1FD9) was used as a suitable structural template to build the 3D structure by MODELLER.19 The input parameters of MODELLER were set to generate 20 models by applying the default model building routine ‘model’ with fast renement. This procedure selects the best model from several model structures. Further, the diﬀerences among the models are used to evaluate the quality of the protein structure modeling. Energy minimization was performed using the valence force eld and the Swiss-PDB Viewer with steepest descent and conjugated gradient algorithms.24 Energy minimi- zation and relaxation of the loop regions were performed using 300 iterations in a simple minimization method. Again the steepest descent was carried out until the energy showed stability in sequential repetition. The overall conformation of the Cht Mip model was very similar to the template, and even the amino acids involved in the rapamycin binding were well conserved. It has two domains, namely the N-terminal and C- terminal. The N-terminal domain is mainly responsible for 18952 | RSC Adv., 2016, 6, 18946–18957 dimerisation and the C-terminal has peptidyl prolyl cis–trans isomerase activity and contributes signicantly toward the binding of ligands. Thus, the 3D model of Cht Mip was considered to be reasonable. 3.2 Protein structure validation

The stereo-chemical quality of Chlamydia trachomatis Mip was evaluated using the PROCHECK program to determine the overall stability of the structure. A Ramachandran plot shows the distribution of the main chain torsion angles: the phi/psi angles of 82.6% of the residues fell in the most favored regions, 15.2% of the residues lay in the additional allowed regions, and 2.2% residues fell in the generously allowed regions; no residues were in the disallowed conformations (Fig. 2). Structural superposition of the modeled protein with respect to the template was calculated using pyMOL and found to have a RMSD value of 0.064 Angstrom. The overall confor- mations of the Chlamydia trachomatis Mip model were very similar to the template (Fig. 3). Thus, the predicted three- dimensional model of C. trachomatis Mip was considered to be reliable. 3.4 Pharmacophore modeling The UNPD (229 358) molecules used for screening were ltered based on the Lipinski rule and Adsorption, Digestion, Metab- olism and Excretion (ADME) properties and the resulting molecules were 87 920 in total. LigandScout2.03 27 was used to from protein–ligand generate complexes based on the interactions between Legionella pneu- mophila Mip in complex with rapamycin (2VCD) and E. coli Mip in complex with FK506 (1Q6I) obtained from the Protein Data Bank (PDB). LigandScout is a program for the automatic detection of relevant interaction points between a ligand and This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2016

a protein. Its algorithms perform a stepwise interpretation of the ligand molecules: planar ring detection, assignment of functional group patterns, determination of the hybridization state, and nally the assignment of the Kekule pattern. Mip is mainly mediated by rapamycin’s pipecoline moiety which is attached in a hydrophobic pocket of the binding site. The active site is found between a helix and the inner side of a sheet and shows a mainly hydrophobic character. Phe180, Leu181, Ile187, Tyr213, and Thr215 residues are formed at the base of the pocket. Asp179, Ile187 and Tyr213 are the major contributors in the hydrogen bonding interaction with compounds and are responsible for the main conformational diﬀerences. Utilizing available structural information, we developed a pharmaco- phore model including crucial interactions between the inhib- itor molecules and active-site residues of Mip as restraints. The nal pharmacophore model was constructed by combining the 9 features as 1 hydrogen bond acceptor (HBA) (green color), 5 hydrogen bond donors (HBDs) (red color) and 3 aromatic rings (yellow color) using the consensus score (Fig. 4). The pharma- cophores of the above mentioned groups have been merged in order to get a common pharmacophore of Mip inhibitors. compounds (87 920) and the most active compounds bind in a similar fashion at the enzyme active site. The new pharma- cophore model was employed to superimpose with the Universal Natural Product Database (UNPD) compounds (87 920) resulting in 150 compounds with common chemical features that were chosen based on ranking and unt compounds were discarded (Fig. 5). Before starting the docking, we tested whether the docking program GOLD28 was able to reproduce reasonable results on Mip proteins by docking rapamycin back into the crystal structure of Legionella Mip. The binding mode found in the crystal structure could be reproduced (RMSD: 1.2 Angstroem) (Fig. 6) and GOLD was used to dock the top 150 compounds aer pharmacophore ltering. The crystal structure of Legion- ella Mip as well as our homology models of Chlamydia tracho- matis Mip and mutant structures of Chlamydia trachomatis Mip were used as receptors for docking. Furthermore, we have docked the hit compounds (150) with the native and mutant proteins of C. trachomatis Mip to determine the binding aﬃnity. Interestingly, 8 compounds were selected based on the scoring and hydrogen bonding interactions (Table 2). Out of 8 compounds, 6 compounds were plant species (Table 2). 2 top scoring compounds (UNPD131087 and UNPD175753) from marine sources were chosen for Molecular Dynamics studies to analyze the stability of the native and mutant model of Chla- mydia trachomatis Mip (Fig. 5). Due to extreme conditions of pH, salinity, temperature and stress, synthesis of secondary metabolites are higher in marine species than in terrestrial plants. At extreme conditions only marine species are able to synthesize active compounds. Therefore, compounds from marine sources are advantageous. 18954 | RSC Adv., 2016, 6, 18946–18957

Ser171, Gly214 and Leu225 are responsible for van der Waals interaction formation but this is lost and 2 new residues (Ile-187 and Val-186) make van der Waals interactions due to the mutagenesis. 3.7 Simulation study of native and mutant complexes Molecular dynamics simulations are used to better understand time evolution and the dynamic behavior of protein confor- mations.28–31 It helps to get information on the motion of indi- vidual atoms as a function of time and enables the explanation of the properties of molecules and the interactions between them.32–34 We performed MD simulations to study the eﬀect of specic mutations on the structural characteristics of Cht Mip protein-wild type and the two single mutants (D170L and Y213A) with inhibitors (compound-1 and compound-2) as explained in the Methods section. We have analysed the root mean square deviation (RMSD), root mean square uctuation (RMSF), radius of gyration (Rg), solvent accessible surface area (SASA), number of hydrogen bonds (NH), and variation of

secondary structure pattern between the native and mutant complexes (native, D170L and Y213A with compound-1 and compound-2). Six independent simulations were carried out for the native and mutant complexes for a total of 20 ns of simu- lation time. We found that compound-1 with mutant D170L showed a similar signicantly deviated pattern compared to the native protein in a complex with compound-1 till the end of the simulation (Fig. 10A), whereas the native and mutant Y213A complex with compound-1 tended to reach a higher equilib- rium compared to the native protein in a complex with compound-1 (Fig. 10), and mutant Y213A remained distin- guishable throughout the simulation resulting in a backbone RMSD of 0.1 to 0.4 nm. From 2 ns till the end of the simulation, Cht Mip (native) showed RMSD values of 0.3–0.4 nm. A small variation in the average RMSD of the native and mutant proteins led to the conclusion that the mutations could inu- ence changes in the exibility of the dynamic behavior of protein. Aer 10 ns there is a stable trajectory throughout the simulation. Similarly, we have observed that compound-2 with both mutants D170L and Y213A showed a similar signicantly diﬀerent pattern till 12 ns at which time there were minor diﬀerences in trajectory leading to a stable equilibrium through to the end of the simulation (Fig. 10A), whereas the native and mutant Y213A complex with compound-1 tended to reach a higher equilibrium compared to the native in a complex with compound-1 (Fig. 10), and mutant Y213A remained distin- guishable throughout the simulation resulting in a backbone RMSD of 0.1 to 0.4 nm. Aer 10 ns, all the complexes throughout the simulation tended to reach a stable trajectory. The higher RMSD obtained for all complexes limited to 0.4 nm demonstrates that the simulations produced stable trajectories, and provided an appropriate basis for further investigation.

The radius of gyration is used to calculate the mass weighted root mean square distance of atoms from their centre of mass. The overall Cht Mip structure at various time points during the trajectory can be analyzed for competence, shape and folding in the plot of Rg (Fig. 10). Throughout the simulation, both compound-1 and compound-2 with mutant proteins D170L and Y213A exhibited a similar pattern for the Rg value, out of which mutant D170L showed a higher deviation with a Rg score of 1.25 nm (Fig. 10). In the simulation of the Y213A protein, we found that the aggregate with a Rg score of 1.3 nm is decreasing in the complex with both compound-1 and compound-2 followed by stabilisation aer 10 ns as is observed in all the complexes towards the end of the simulation (Fig. 10 and 11). We have measured the C-RMSF to observe the overall exi- bility of atomic positions in the trajectory for the native and complexes. The mutant D170L complex with mutant compound-1 shows a signicant change in the protein structure conformation (as compared to the backbone RMSD) with an increase in the C-RMSF also observed (Fig. 10). This suggests that the Y213A mutation causes the binding of compound-1 & 2 to make the backbone become more exible for motion. The Y213A-compound-2 mutation aﬀects the interacting residues at a maximum of 0.46 nm (Fig. 10). Furthermore, the exibility of mutant Y213A was found to be inconsistent with the native Cht Mip. This is due to the restriction of the surrounding residues 18956 | RSC Adv., 2016, 6, 18946–18957 caused by the active site of the protein due to the mutation in Cht Mip. The results suggest that there exists a signicant change of structural deviation in the mutant complex Y213A when compared to the native.

the hydrophobic core forming the mutant D170L complex with compound-1 and compound-2, SASA was evaluated. Results show higher values of SASA (35 nm) with time when compared to the native protein (Fig. 9 and 11). In the case of the mutant Y213A in a complex with compound-1 and compound-2, small diﬀerences of SASA (32 nm) were observed. Hence, the ndings are in direct correlation with changes to the solvent accessible surface area (SASA) which reects that the major exposure was due to the loss of hydrophobic contact formation between the catalytic residues and compound-1 and compound-2. The numbers of hydrogen bonds formed between cpd-1 and cpd2 and the protein (native and mutant) during the MD simulation were also calculated (Fig. 9 and 10). From our analysis, it is well revealed that the native complex forms a greater number of NH bonds with native and D170L-cpd1 with an average of 2–3 hydrogen bonds (Fig. 10). Meanwhile the mutant complex Y213A-compound-1 (UNPD131087) exhibited a fewer number of intermolecular hydrogen bonds, an average of (cid:4)1–2 (Fig. 10). The number of hydrogen bonds with the native Cht Mip and D170L compound-2 (175753) was on average (cid:4)3–4 (Fig. 10). While the mutant complex Y213A-compound-2 (UNPD175753) exhibited a fewer number of hydrogen bonds with an average of (cid:4)1–2 (Fig. 11).

In the present work, the 3D structure of the native and mutant Chlamydia trachomatis Mip was constructed based on the X-ray structure of Legionella pneumophila Mip using homology modeling. The model was then validated and further used for docking analysis. We developed a pharmacophore model based on the important features of rapamycin and FK506. The new pharmacophore model was used to superimpose with the Universal Natural Product Database (UNPD) compounds and resulting compounds with common chemical features were chosen. Furthermore the lead molecules were docked into the active site of the native and mutant Chlamydia trachomatis Mip. Docking analysis showed that the native Chlamydia trachoamtis Mip has the highest GOLD score of 85.75 in terms of compound- 1 (UNPD131087) binding compared to the D142L mutant that has a score of 83.21 and Y213A that has a score of 79.54. Simi- larly, compound-2 (UNPD175753) has a GOLD score of 85.60 and D142L has a score of 82.47 and Y213A has a score of 78.86 which indicates that the binding aﬃnity is highly aﬀected in both of the mutants due to changes in the conformation of the active site to which resistance has been developed. Molecular dynamics simulation analysis infers changes in the binding pattern and structural modication in the binding site by means of Rg, SASA, RMSD and RMSF.
